    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1954-04-23T16:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1954-04-23T16:00:00-05:00" n="779"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d779">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">740.5/4–2354: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                            <gloss type="to">Department of State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">top secret<lb/>
                            <gloss target="#t_niact1">niact</gloss>
                        </hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Paris</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1954-04-23T22:00:00+01:00"
                            >April 23, 1954—10 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <gloss target="#t_Dulte1">Dulte</gloss> 8. No distribution. Eyes only for Acting
                    Secretary from Secretary. Please pass following message to The President: <quote
                        rend="blockquote">
                        <p>“I am deeply touched by, and grateful for, your message.<note n="1"
                                xml:id="d779fn1">For text of the President’s message, see telegram
                                    <gloss target="#t_Tedul1">Tedul</gloss> 5, Apr. 23, <ref
                                    target="#pg_1366">p. 1366</ref>.</note> The situation here is
                            tragic. France is almost visibly collapsing under our eyes. There is, of
                            course, no military or logical reason why loss of Dien Bien Phu should
                            lead to collapse of French will, in relation both to Indochina and
                                <gloss target="#t_EDC1">EDC</gloss>. It seems to me that Dien Bien
                            Phu has become a symbol out of all proportion to its military
                            importance. It does not seem possible to change this situation, although
                            we are not giving up hope and are doing everything possible to keep
                            their spirit up. The position today is a little better as regards <gloss
                                target="#t_EDC1">EDC</gloss>, but probably if Dien Bien Phu falls,
                            the government will be taken over by defeatists.</p>
                        <pb facs="1407" n="1375" xml:id="pg_1375"/>
                        <p>I shall talk to <persName corresp="#p_ESA1">Eden</persName> about
                                <persName corresp="#p_CWS1">Winston</persName>’s message and give
                            you my considered judgment shortly. My basic reaction is yours, namely,
                            that a meeting should solemnize and publicize a major decision
                            sufficiently explored and developed in advance to be sure that it is in
                            hand. Faithfully yours, <persName corresp="#p_DJF1"
                            >Foster</persName>.”</p>
                    </quote>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_DJF1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Dulles</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
